Fert vallum et arma miles, διε. “ Bears the stake, and arms, as a sol— dier, and can yield obedience to withered eunuchs.” The poet expresses his indignation, that Romans, hardy enough to endure the toils of military service, can, at the same time, be so wanting in spirit as to yield obedieneo to the orders of eunuchs. The allusion, in the words fert vallum, is to that part of Roman discipline which compelled each soldier to car-ry, among other things, a certain number of stakes (usually three or four) to be used in encamping.—Spadonibus. The allusion seems to be principally to the eunuch Mardion, who, according to Plutarch, along with Pothinus, Iras, and Charmion, had the chief direction of Cleopatra’s affairs (Ὑφ’ ὧν τὰ μέγιστα διοικεῖται τῆς ἡγεμονίας.
